            <term xml:id="term-k000271-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">cai</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000271-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">踩</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000271-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">踩</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000271-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">cǎi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000271-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">ts`ai</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000271-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000271-1" >step</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000271</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">Cai 踩 was a term used during the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasty to describe the scale and dimensions of <term ref="/keyword/k000019">dougong</term> (bracket sets), commonly used in the form of “N-cai dougong.” The 
                  character cai, also written as 跴, can also appear as 彩, 採, or 采 (Kan Duo, 1931). The Kangxi Dictionary defines 踩, as “to jump.” As an architectural term, it first appears 
                  in the Qing dynasty Yangshi Lei architectural drawings (Zhou Junliang, Zhang Fengwu, Wang Qiheng, 2022), and later in texts such as Yingzao suanli, Yingzao fashi taoben, and 
                  Yingzao fayuan. There are two main interpretations:</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">1. In Qing dynasty sources, cai is associated with the number of layers and the height of dougong structures. The number of dougong layers corresponds to the number 
                  of cai (Liang Sicheng, 1932: 9; Zhou Junliang, Zhang Fengwu, Wang Qiheng, 2022). The term cai could also specify the height dimensions of components associated with dougong, such 
                  as the sectional height of the zhengxin fang (central beam) (Liang Sicheng, 1932: 11).</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">2. It is associated with the projection depth (chutiao) of the dougong. This meaning first appears in an illustration made by late Qing craftsmen published in the Yingzao 
                  Fashi Taoben (Li Jie, 1925: juan 30, appendix 5), but is not found in official texts. Liang Sicheng also adopted this interpretation, simplifying the calculation of cai to “twice the 
                  number of angqiao (rising arms) or zhuajia (struts), plus one” (Qing-Style Construction Standards, Liang 1934: 22, 24). This interpretation has since been widely adopted by later scholars.</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">踩是清代用於描述斗栱尺度規模的术语，常見斗栱為“N踩”的用法。踩，同跴，亦可作彩或採或采（闞鐸，1931）。作爲建築術語，最早見於清樣式雷圖檔（周俊良、張鳳梧、王其亨，2022），又見於《營造算例》、
                  《營造法式陶本》及《營造法原》。根據時間先後，有以下兩種釋義：</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">1. 清代文獻中踩與斗栱层数和高度相關聯，斗栱層數即踩數（梁思成，1932：9；周俊良、張鳳梧、王其亨，2022），踩亦可用來規定與斗栱相關聯構件的高度尺寸，如正心枋的斷面高度等（梁思成，1932：11）。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">2. 與斗栱出跳數相關聯。這一含義最早見於《營造法式陶本》晚清工匠所做插圖（李诫，1925：卷三十附五），梁思成也採用這個觀點，將踩數的計算簡化為昂翹數或拽架數的兩倍加一。
                  （《清式營造則例》梁 1934，22,24）後來學者普遍沿用這個釋義。</p>
            </note>
